WEBVTT

00:00:36.070 --> 00:00:36.970
Oh, there you go.

00:00:36.970 --> 00:00:38.000
Okay.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:41.280
So for those of you who
saw the keynote yesterday,

00:00:41.280 --> 00:00:44.320
you probably noticed that Apple's
been rather busy this year.

00:00:44.320 --> 00:00:48.270
And open source has certainly
been no exception for us.

00:00:48.270 --> 00:00:53.400
So there's going to be a
veritable cavalcade of speakers

00:00:53.400 --> 00:00:59.010
coming up here after me to
describe their various projects.

00:00:59.050 --> 00:01:01.590
But I'll give sort of a general overview
and introduce the first of them.

00:01:02.570 --> 00:01:04.240
These are also some important resources.

00:01:04.350 --> 00:01:08.820
As always, you can find our most recent
Darwin sources and pointers

00:01:08.820 --> 00:01:12.270
to other important open source
projects at developer.apple.com.

00:01:12.350 --> 00:01:16.680
OpenDarwin.org is another project we
launched about a year ago in cooperation

00:01:16.680 --> 00:01:19.120
with the Internet Software Consortium.

00:01:19.120 --> 00:01:22.240
So you can get information
there at OpenDarwin.org,

00:01:22.240 --> 00:01:24.680
and that's been very successful for us.

00:01:24.680 --> 00:01:28.550
And then, of course,
we have our wonderful Fink brethren,

00:01:28.550 --> 00:01:31.820
who have a Fink.SourceForge.net address.

00:01:32.410 --> 00:01:35.900
And then, of course,
have to mention FreeBSD.

00:01:36.950 --> 00:01:38.860
Yay!

00:01:39.090 --> 00:01:43.260
So let me talk a little
bit about OpenDarwin.

00:01:43.260 --> 00:01:47.390
They've started doing something we
really hoped could be done by an external

00:01:47.390 --> 00:01:51.420
but yet loosely affiliated project,
which is producing their own

00:01:51.420 --> 00:01:53.000
Darwin standalone releases.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:56.060
Those of you who ran the
Apple Darwin releases might

00:01:56.070 --> 00:01:59.220
have noticed that they tended
to come out fairly seldom,

00:01:59.220 --> 00:02:01.920
and there were general issues
with them that we didn't always

00:02:01.920 --> 00:02:04.720
have the engineering resources
to fix in a timely manner.

00:02:05.350 --> 00:02:09.340
So with the additional volunteer
resources that OpenDarwin.org

00:02:09.440 --> 00:02:12.580
brings to the table,
they've been able to do some

00:02:12.580 --> 00:02:16.380
very high quality releases of
Darwin for both the x86 and PowerPC.

00:02:16.380 --> 00:02:18.510
So we're very happy to see that.

00:02:18.540 --> 00:02:22.840
Another thing that they've been doing is
providing RPMs for all of the components.

00:02:22.860 --> 00:02:25.820
So you now have an RPM database
installed that you can query

00:02:25.820 --> 00:02:29.260
to see where various components
belong or where they came from.

00:02:29.260 --> 00:02:33.000
Obviously updates and whatnot
are possible in the future.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:35.320
They're not doing that yet,
but that's certainly an option.

00:02:35.320 --> 00:02:38.650
They're doing that in conjunction now
with real package management behind the

00:02:38.650 --> 00:02:41.890
operating system and they're providing
SRPMs which correspond directly to

00:02:41.890 --> 00:02:43.770
what they use to build the binary bits.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:47.870
The Darwin Ports Project,
which you'll also hear quite a bit more

00:02:47.870 --> 00:02:52.330
about in this chain of presentations,
has been doing what it can to bring more

00:02:52.330 --> 00:02:54.760
third-party software to the platform.

00:02:54.760 --> 00:02:58.650
And they have a WebDAV mountable
packages collection already

00:02:58.650 --> 00:03:01.140
at packages.opendarwin.org.

00:03:01.180 --> 00:03:04.590
So you can simply connect to that
in the finder and double-click on

00:03:04.590 --> 00:03:06.620
one of the packages there and poof.

00:03:06.620 --> 00:03:09.230
Well,
I don't mean that the way it sounds.

00:03:12.370 --> 00:03:13.160
and many more.

00:03:13.310 --> 00:03:14.300
I mean, bingo.

00:03:14.300 --> 00:03:14.300
That's the word.

00:03:14.300 --> 00:03:19.700
So we've also changed the way
we do open source releases.

00:03:19.700 --> 00:03:21.800
In the past,
what we did was we essentially

00:03:21.930 --> 00:03:26.820
just pushed out copies of our live
CVS repository at periodic intervals,

00:03:26.820 --> 00:03:31.220
and we had some stuff that was just live,
you know, on a minute-to-minute basis.

00:03:31.220 --> 00:03:34.110
And that was cool from the
perspective of being able to see

00:03:34.110 --> 00:03:38.010
sort of the work in progress,
but what it really didn't do was

00:03:38.110 --> 00:03:42.890
give you any directly correspondent
bits to Mac OS X or Darwin,

00:03:42.960 --> 00:03:46.310
e.g., you didn't know that what
you were looking at in CVS was

00:03:46.560 --> 00:03:49.700
what you were actually running,
nor were those bits necessarily

00:03:49.700 --> 00:03:53.260
compilable at any given time because
you were looking at top of tree.

00:03:53.260 --> 00:03:55.360
There might be works in progress.

00:03:55.360 --> 00:03:58.160
There were obviously synchronization
issues between different projects.

00:03:58.160 --> 00:04:01.540
One might be n steps ahead of another,
but there's interdependencies because

00:04:01.560 --> 00:04:03.540
someone hasn't checked that stuff in yet.

00:04:03.540 --> 00:04:08.480
So we looked at that,
and what we started doing instead

00:04:08.620 --> 00:04:14.060
is breaking our releases into what
we call on-cycle and off-cycle,

00:04:14.060 --> 00:04:18.120
which is on-cycle releases are
snapshots of the exact sources

00:04:18.120 --> 00:04:20.080
that we use to build the product.

00:04:20.080 --> 00:04:23.730
So now when you get an on-cycle snapshot,
you know it corresponds to a

00:04:23.730 --> 00:04:27.050
given release of Mac OS X or a
given software update of Mac OS X,

00:04:27.100 --> 00:04:31.750
and they're synchronized together because
we didn't have the tag information

00:04:31.810 --> 00:04:32.980
exported before that would have let
you sort of read through the data.

00:04:33.010 --> 00:04:36.460
So we're able to sort of recreate
that state of affairs for yourself.

00:04:36.460 --> 00:04:38.770
And some stuff is still done off-cycle.

00:04:38.900 --> 00:04:43.180
Darwin streaming server, rendezvous, GDB,
GCC, various GPL projects,

00:04:43.180 --> 00:04:46.000
you can still get the
CVS top of tree for that.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:47.600
So we're not doing it for
absolutely everything,

00:04:47.600 --> 00:04:49.730
but for the majority of the bits,
we're trying to move

00:04:49.730 --> 00:04:52.000
to an on-cycle model.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:55.300
The source is now available
via web DAV as well as CVS,

00:04:55.330 --> 00:05:02.080
so you can mount the appropriate volume
and just drag the sources around.

00:05:02.080 --> 00:05:02.620
And we're continuously adding.

00:05:02.620 --> 00:05:02.620
So we're continuously adding.

00:05:02.620 --> 00:05:06.000
We're continuously adding to what we've
previously released as open source.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:09.800
There's a lot of new open
source initiatives at Apple.

00:05:11.480 --> 00:05:11.960
Some of those.

00:05:11.960 --> 00:05:14.900
You've probably heard the
announcements about WebCor.

00:05:14.900 --> 00:05:18.720
So the Safari folks have been working
very closely with the KHTML team,

00:05:18.720 --> 00:05:21.150
and you'll hear more about
that in this presentation,

00:05:21.150 --> 00:05:22.840
and the JavaScript stuff as well.

00:05:22.840 --> 00:05:25.840
Of course, there's also the X11
product now and the SDK.

00:05:25.950 --> 00:05:30.090
And we've been working all
over the map in the third-party

00:05:30.090 --> 00:05:34.740
software and FreeBSD areas to
update components of Mac OS X.

00:05:34.980 --> 00:05:39.180
We have a new TCL, new Python, new Perl,
new Samba.

00:05:39.180 --> 00:05:42.820
We've synced up LibC with
FreeBSD 5.0 to bring in all the

00:05:42.820 --> 00:05:44.780
WCharty support and thread safety.

00:05:44.780 --> 00:05:49.480
So there's too many projects to mention
that we've synchronized for Panther.

00:05:51.990 --> 00:05:55.370
So coming up next,
we'll have someone from the

00:05:55.430 --> 00:06:00.020
Open Darwin project talk a little bit
more about Open Darwin and Darwin ports.

00:06:00.060 --> 00:06:01.630
So let me introduce him now.

00:06:01.700 --> 00:06:04.230
Kevin Van Vechten of
the Open Darwin project

00:06:04.230 --> 00:06:05.780
and recently of Apple.

00:06:14.570 --> 00:06:18.500
I'm here to talk a little bit
about the Open Darwin project.

00:06:18.500 --> 00:06:21.880
Open Darwin, as was mentioned,
was started about a year ago.

00:06:21.880 --> 00:06:27.300
And what it is, is a community supported
site outside of Apple.

00:06:27.300 --> 00:06:29.840
It's hosted by the
Internet Software Consortium.

00:06:29.840 --> 00:06:35.440
Neither the ISC nor Apple exercise
editorial control over Open Darwin.

00:06:35.760 --> 00:06:39.790
So what that means is Open Darwin is
free to explore technologies that maybe

00:06:39.790 --> 00:06:44.110
Apple doesn't feel is very high priority,
but the developer community as a whole

00:06:44.110 --> 00:06:46.080
would like to see incorporated in Darwin.

00:06:46.080 --> 00:06:50.710
And once it's working there,
we can advocate within

00:06:50.710 --> 00:06:56.820
Apple incorporating those changes
into a future Mac OS X release.

00:06:56.820 --> 00:07:00.000
Open Darwin provides
support for Darwin users.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:04.820
It provides mailing lists,
how-to articles, documentation.

00:07:05.760 --> 00:07:08.840
It provides a lot of information
for using various Darwin commands,

00:07:08.910 --> 00:07:11.520
which of course are also
applicable to Mac OS X.

00:07:11.520 --> 00:07:14.110
And most importantly,
Open Darwin provides

00:07:14.110 --> 00:07:15.880
resources for developers.

00:07:15.900 --> 00:07:21.520
We provide the same mailing lists
and documentation for information

00:07:21.520 --> 00:07:27.220
relevant to porting third-party
open source Unix software to Darwin.

00:07:27.220 --> 00:07:32.700
And just kind of being a central point
for information about Darwin development.

00:07:32.700 --> 00:07:35.690
Which of course directly
applies to Open Darwin.

00:07:35.760 --> 00:07:37.460
And that's why we're so
excited to be here today.

00:07:37.460 --> 00:07:39.250
And we're excited to be here
today to talk about the Mac OS X,

00:07:39.250 --> 00:07:43.620
because a lot of key
Mac OS X technologies like I/O Kit and

00:07:43.620 --> 00:07:45.370
Core Foundation are also part of Darwin.

00:07:46.390 --> 00:07:51.140
So one of our primary goals in OpenDarwin
is to stay synchronized with Mac OS X.

00:07:51.140 --> 00:07:55.680
We recognize there's a much larger
developer community around Mac OS X than

00:07:56.010 --> 00:07:58.790
there is focused on pure Darwin.

00:07:58.800 --> 00:08:02.610
So as much as possible,
we want to make it easy to take

00:08:02.610 --> 00:08:08.300
individual components of the
Darwin operating system from OpenDarwin.

00:08:08.300 --> 00:08:12.720
You could compile them on your
own and substitute a piece of

00:08:12.870 --> 00:08:15.590
Mac OS X with the custom component.

00:08:17.350 --> 00:08:20.160
As part of that,
we provide binary releases of

00:08:20.160 --> 00:08:22.540
Darwin and components of Darwin.

00:08:22.540 --> 00:08:25.890
So if you're interested in
playing with a particular version,

00:08:25.890 --> 00:08:27.820
there's a place where you can go.

00:08:27.820 --> 00:08:28.540
It would be pre-built.

00:08:28.580 --> 00:08:30.440
You could download it, install from a CD.

00:08:30.440 --> 00:08:35.600
We also are working to provide an easy
build system for Darwin so that you

00:08:35.640 --> 00:08:41.540
can look at any particular library,
command, build it quickly and easily,

00:08:41.540 --> 00:08:45.620
modify it a little bit, rebuild it again,
install it on your system,

00:08:45.620 --> 00:08:48.280
and use that for debugging,
for development.

00:08:48.280 --> 00:08:52.180
And also, importantly,
is OpenDarwin's a staging

00:08:52.180 --> 00:08:53.670
area for external development.

00:08:53.680 --> 00:08:57.790
So, for example,
in our current OpenDarwin sources,

00:08:57.790 --> 00:09:04.050
we have some of OpenBSD's sys trace
work as an experiment for dealing with

00:09:04.240 --> 00:09:07.680
access control on various sys calls.

00:09:07.680 --> 00:09:13.550
We also have FreeBSD commands brought
over from the FreeBSD project,

00:09:13.550 --> 00:09:15.870
integrated into OpenDarwin,
and we've also got some of the open

00:09:15.870 --> 00:09:19.610
source projects that we've tested there,
and then they were able to bring some of

00:09:19.610 --> 00:09:25.800
those in as part of Panther to keep us
up to speed and keep us synchronized with

00:09:25.900 --> 00:09:29.000
the other open source projects out there.

00:09:30.050 --> 00:09:34.360
So OpenDarwin focuses a lot on
open collaboration for developing

00:09:34.660 --> 00:09:37.980
software that pertains to Darwin and,
of course, Mac OS X as a whole.

00:09:37.980 --> 00:09:40.800
We host projects relevant to Darwin.

00:09:40.800 --> 00:09:43.680
For example,
KDE Darwin is currently hosted there.

00:09:43.680 --> 00:09:46.450
It's one of our larger
projects in terms of code base.

00:09:46.460 --> 00:09:50.490
DarwinPorts, as mentioned,
is another project hosted at OpenDarwin,

00:09:50.490 --> 00:09:52.740
which is one of our more active projects.

00:09:54.400 --> 00:09:58.740
We provide the infrastructure so that
people can create projects and allow

00:09:58.740 --> 00:10:03.390
developers from the community to sign up,
get access to CVS.

00:10:03.520 --> 00:10:07.660
And we're also working to have a mirrored
version of a lot of the Apple projects,

00:10:07.740 --> 00:10:09.900
say Streaming Server or HeaderDoc.

00:10:09.980 --> 00:10:13.740
Eventually, we want to see some of those
in a repository at OpenDarwin.

00:10:13.740 --> 00:10:19.490
So third-party and community
contributions can be put into CVS there,

00:10:19.490 --> 00:10:23.660
tested, integrated,
and then advocated back at Apple.

00:10:23.940 --> 00:10:27.540
So that's a potential enhancement
or bug fix or whatever.

00:10:29.440 --> 00:10:32.410
So the Darwin Ports project,
being one of the most active

00:10:32.410 --> 00:10:37.350
projects at OpenDarwin,
is a project designed to port

00:10:37.440 --> 00:10:39.300
open source software to Darwin.

00:10:39.300 --> 00:10:45.620
Its main focus is the easy installation,
removal, and upgrading of software

00:10:45.700 --> 00:10:47.990
from source or binaries.

00:10:48.060 --> 00:10:51.500
The binary support is
still a work in progress.

00:10:52.960 --> 00:10:56.080
One of the reasons why I'm mentioning
it here in OpenDarwin is there's

00:10:56.080 --> 00:11:00.470
a fair chance that we'll be using
Darwin Ports as means of building the

00:11:00.530 --> 00:11:05.220
individual components of the underlying
Darwin operating system at OpenDarwin,

00:11:05.220 --> 00:11:08.810
so that there would be a port for each,
not only third party and

00:11:08.910 --> 00:11:11.830
open source Unix software,
but also for each of the

00:11:11.870 --> 00:11:13.380
components of Darwin.

00:11:13.380 --> 00:11:15.920
So it would be as easy as saying,
you know,

00:11:15.920 --> 00:11:19.600
build and install a core foundation
on a single command line,

00:11:19.630 --> 00:11:21.540
and it could do that for you.

00:11:22.560 --> 00:11:28.560
There's also a Cocoa user
interface to Darwin Ports.

00:11:28.740 --> 00:11:33.550
It lets you browse through all the
available software that currently

00:11:33.550 --> 00:11:35.980
has a port file representation.

00:11:35.980 --> 00:11:39.320
You can choose what you want to build,
click on it, it'll build,

00:11:39.320 --> 00:11:40.760
install on your system.

00:11:43.780 --> 00:11:48.970
So the most important thing I want to
mention today is that OpenDarwin really

00:11:48.970 --> 00:11:56.070
is a third party independent project and
it does need your help to be successful.

00:11:56.070 --> 00:11:59.340
And if everybody joins the
mailing list and discuss any

00:11:59.440 --> 00:12:03.190
Darwin technical issues they have,
it can really be a good central

00:12:03.400 --> 00:12:06.370
resource for development for Mac OS X,
for Darwin,

00:12:06.480 --> 00:12:08.620
for porting Unix applications.

00:12:09.760 --> 00:12:13.750
Also, we have a Bugzilla
database at OpenDarwin,

00:12:13.750 --> 00:12:18.790
so there's a good opportunity
to report any bugs with Darwin,

00:12:18.790 --> 00:12:22.680
with any libraries or
commands there at OpenDarwin,

00:12:22.680 --> 00:12:27.330
as well as submitting a patch or at
least making a reference to saying,

00:12:27.400 --> 00:12:31.600
well, this isn't a problem in NetBSD or
this isn't a problem in FreeBSD.

00:12:31.600 --> 00:12:34.890
And then somebody at OpenDarwin
can take a look at that,

00:12:35.070 --> 00:12:38.180
figure out what needs to change,
and we can incorporate

00:12:38.180 --> 00:12:39.740
that back into Mac OS X.

00:12:39.760 --> 00:12:43.660
There's a couple mailing
lists at OpenDarwin.

00:12:43.750 --> 00:12:47.890
If you're interested in proposing
projects relevant to Darwin or

00:12:47.890 --> 00:12:52.190
discussing new features or enhancements,
that would be appropriate for

00:12:52.190 --> 00:12:53.900
the discuss list at OpenDarwin.

00:12:53.900 --> 00:12:56.860
If you're interested
in submitting patches,

00:12:57.100 --> 00:13:00.260
code, documentation,
that is appropriate for the

00:13:00.330 --> 00:13:02.400
hackers list at OpenDarwin.

00:13:04.040 --> 00:13:08.750
and there's a couple interesting
other sections pertaining

00:13:08.890 --> 00:13:14.140
to open source and Darwin,
QuickTime Streaming Server, Rendezvous,

00:13:14.140 --> 00:13:19.520
GCC, Unix sysadmin tools.

00:13:19.520 --> 00:13:24.030
And up next is Don Melton and he'll
be talking a bit about Safari.

00:13:31.210 --> 00:13:32.300
Hi, I'm Don Melton.

00:13:32.300 --> 00:13:35.450
I'm the Internet Technologies Manager at
Apple Computer,

00:13:35.450 --> 00:13:39.280
and I'm here to talk to you today
about Safari and open source.

00:13:39.280 --> 00:13:41.770
And I'll give you a little
roadmap to some other sessions

00:13:41.770 --> 00:13:43.010
here at the conference.

00:13:44.500 --> 00:13:51.000
[Transcript missing]

00:13:51.220 --> 00:13:52.980
Why is Safari so successful?

00:13:52.980 --> 00:13:55.710
I mean, because people are not
only downloading it,

00:13:55.710 --> 00:13:58.320
I think 5 million so far,
something like that,

00:13:58.360 --> 00:14:00.030
they're actually also using it.

00:14:00.060 --> 00:14:02.190
Some of them are making it
their default web browser.

00:14:02.190 --> 00:14:05.700
I think of three reasons
why it's so popular.

00:14:05.700 --> 00:14:08.080
First off, innovative features.

00:14:08.080 --> 00:14:10.570
It's got a superior user experience.

00:14:10.620 --> 00:14:13.040
This is a full featured web browser.

00:14:13.110 --> 00:14:14.890
People take it seriously.

00:14:14.910 --> 00:14:16.730
It can do things for you.

00:14:17.590 --> 00:14:19.300
Secondly, solid quality.

00:14:19.300 --> 00:14:22.310
Real world compatibility with the web.

00:14:22.310 --> 00:14:25.120
By that I mean pages
look the way you expect,

00:14:25.120 --> 00:14:28.920
and they look the way web
designers expect them to look too,

00:14:28.920 --> 00:14:31.710
especially if they
write to web standards,

00:14:31.730 --> 00:14:33.850
but hey, even if they don't.

00:14:33.940 --> 00:14:36.930
But most importantly,
impressive performance.

00:14:37.040 --> 00:14:39.260
It's the fastest browser on Mac OS X.

00:14:39.380 --> 00:14:42.550
We beat everybody not only
on the standard benchmarks,

00:14:42.560 --> 00:14:45.140
but we also beat them
in just real world use,

00:14:45.140 --> 00:14:47.300
loading pages, scrolling, reading.

00:14:47.320 --> 00:14:49.990
Resizing, launching especially.

00:14:50.100 --> 00:14:51.670
1.0 is faster.

00:14:51.670 --> 00:14:57.180
And now the underlying technology within
Safari is built right into Mac OS X.

00:14:57.180 --> 00:15:02.690
And it's this underlying technology that
I want to talk a little bit about today

00:15:02.690 --> 00:15:05.800
because it's based on open standards.

00:15:05.860 --> 00:15:12.080
Firstly,
it's based on W3C standards like HTML4,

00:15:12.080 --> 00:15:16.400
XML, CSS, DOM, so on and so forth.

00:15:16.460 --> 00:15:19.780
But more importantly,
it's based on open source.

00:15:19.780 --> 00:15:22.910
And that's open source
from the KDE project.

00:15:22.970 --> 00:15:26.150
The KDE project,
as many of you might know,

00:15:26.150 --> 00:15:31.600
is an open source desktop available
on Linux and other Unix platforms.

00:15:31.600 --> 00:15:35.620
It has all sorts of applications
and utilities and libraries.

00:15:35.640 --> 00:15:39.710
And one of the big applications
is the Conqueror web browser.

00:15:39.710 --> 00:15:42.800
And the Conqueror web
browser uses two libraries.

00:15:42.800 --> 00:15:43.250
Thank you.

00:15:43.250 --> 00:15:46.430
Two libraries, KHTML and KJS.

00:15:46.460 --> 00:15:51.390
And we're using those same
libraries within Safari.

00:15:51.390 --> 00:15:55.450
First, we're using it in a
framework called WebCore,

00:15:55.450 --> 00:16:02.350
which is just an adapter
built on KHTML from KDE.

00:16:02.430 --> 00:16:04.420
It uses most of the KHTML sources,
about 95% of them.

00:16:04.420 --> 00:16:08.280
And it has glue code to
the rest of Mac OS X,

00:16:08.860 --> 00:16:11.830
which has also been open sourced.

00:16:12.560 --> 00:16:16.750
We also use JavaScript Core,
which is just a simple wrapper around

00:16:16.750 --> 00:16:20.140
the KJS JavaScript interpreter,
also from KDE.

00:16:20.140 --> 00:16:21.490
But that's not all.

00:16:21.490 --> 00:16:25.010
Safari also contains other
open source components in

00:16:25.150 --> 00:16:30.700
WebCor and in JavaScript Core,
such as the XPAT XML parser,

00:16:30.700 --> 00:16:36.100
the PCRE regular expression library,
and even, shock,

00:16:36.180 --> 00:16:38.670
portions of Mozilla code.

00:16:38.740 --> 00:16:41.300
I mean, a lot of people are actually
surprised at that when they

00:16:41.380 --> 00:16:42.500
go perusing through WebCor.

00:16:44.690 --> 00:16:48.350
So why open source?

00:16:48.410 --> 00:16:49.680
It's all about the technology.

00:16:49.710 --> 00:16:52.790
It's not just that it's
a good development model,

00:16:52.790 --> 00:16:55.460
but for us, it was a technology decision.

00:16:55.460 --> 00:16:59.020
KHTML and KGS are just
tremendous technologies.

00:16:59.080 --> 00:17:03.910
I'd like to tip my hat to KDE developers
for their fine work for that.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:06.700
And let me just go into
detail as exactly why.

00:17:06.700 --> 00:17:08.840
One, it's small.

00:17:08.850 --> 00:17:13.150
KHTML and KGS together are
about 140,000 lines of code.

00:17:13.970 --> 00:17:17.730
That's almost an order of
magnitude smaller than some

00:17:17.880 --> 00:17:20.430
other projects and web browsers.

00:17:20.830 --> 00:17:24.700
and it's fast because if
you have less source code,

00:17:24.700 --> 00:17:27.210
you've got less binary code.

00:17:27.230 --> 00:17:30.470
Less binary code means
you execute things faster.

00:17:30.470 --> 00:17:32.340
It's also designed for speed.

00:17:32.340 --> 00:17:35.030
It's really designed well.

00:17:35.410 --> 00:17:37.160
and it's easy to modify.

00:17:37.160 --> 00:17:40.100
This is a fun source base to hack.

00:17:40.140 --> 00:17:44.660
It's just a hoot to get in
there and mess around with it.

00:17:44.660 --> 00:17:45.780
It's easy to understand.

00:17:45.780 --> 00:17:50.430
There's not layers and layers
of abstraction to figure out.

00:17:50.430 --> 00:17:51.680
It's very, very straightforward.

00:17:51.680 --> 00:17:54.460
And we've tried to maintain that
with the rest of our development.

