00:21:11.380 --> 00:21:12.000
Hello.

00:21:12.030 --> 00:21:12.960
I'm Richard Blanchard.

00:21:13.100 --> 00:21:15.480
I'm the Apple engineering
manager for printing.

00:21:15.480 --> 00:21:16.960
And today I'm going to give
you a little bit of insight in

00:21:16.960 --> 00:21:20.190
what we've been doing with our
printing projects inside of Darwin.

00:21:20.440 --> 00:21:23.500
A year ago in this exact session,
I was incredibly pleased and excited to

00:21:23.500 --> 00:21:26.460
announce that we were including CUPS,
Common Unix Printing System,

00:21:26.460 --> 00:21:28.800
into Darwin and into Mac OS X.

00:21:28.800 --> 00:21:31.490
And that's the basis of our
Jaguar printing system and

00:21:31.560 --> 00:21:33.240
our Panther printing system.

00:21:33.240 --> 00:21:36.140
Over the last year,
I spent a lot of time rolling

00:21:36.140 --> 00:21:40.200
important fixes from the ongoing
CUPS mainline development.

00:21:40.200 --> 00:21:42.280
We used CUPS 1.1.15.

00:21:42.280 --> 00:21:45.440
CUPS since then has moved on to .16, .17,
.18.

00:21:45.970 --> 00:21:49.000
We've taken bug fixes from those
changes and security fixes and

00:21:49.010 --> 00:21:50.890
rolled them back onto our .15 base.

00:21:50.900 --> 00:21:52.460
That's kept us pretty busy.

00:21:52.460 --> 00:21:55.210
Over that year,
I've been reading some postings

00:21:55.210 --> 00:21:58.210
from people who were concerned,
maybe was the right word,

00:21:58.210 --> 00:22:00.070
that we were maybe stagnating.

00:22:00.260 --> 00:22:03.310
Darwin and Mac OS X was
using this .15 base.

00:22:03.430 --> 00:22:05.820
Meanwhile, CUPS was running ahead and
was all the way up to .18.

00:22:05.820 --> 00:22:09.310
That's just not the case.

00:22:09.400 --> 00:22:11.260
As I said,
we've been moving these bug fixes back.

00:22:11.340 --> 00:22:13.450
But the reason I really bring
that up is not because I'm really

00:22:13.460 --> 00:22:14.770
oversensitive to these posts.

00:22:15.010 --> 00:22:18.410
But instead, it's because there's an
important point there.

00:22:18.550 --> 00:22:21.130
One of the reasons we went to
CUPS to an open source printing

00:22:21.140 --> 00:22:22.660
system was for transparency.

00:22:22.810 --> 00:22:26.090
It was so the developers could look,
see what we were doing,

00:22:26.090 --> 00:22:29.230
give us feedback before we
actually made a major release.

00:22:29.360 --> 00:22:32.190
And in that same vein,
our CUPS repository,

00:22:32.260 --> 00:22:35.820
our CVS repository is part of Darwin,
is live every day.

00:22:35.940 --> 00:22:38.890
So you can go on to Darwin and
see what we've done any given day.

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:41.440
And we've had our
Panther CUPS development,

00:22:41.440 --> 00:22:44.680
which is based on 1.19,
up there for some time.

00:22:45.610 --> 00:22:49.020
So again, for Panther we're using 1.1.19.

00:22:49.020 --> 00:22:50.740
There are some important
changes in there,

00:22:50.790 --> 00:22:51.900
important fixes, important features.

00:22:51.900 --> 00:22:53.750
There are some bindings
for new languages,

00:22:53.750 --> 00:22:55.180
so there are Java bindings now.

00:22:55.180 --> 00:22:56.680
That'll be in Panther.

00:22:56.680 --> 00:22:59.810
PHP and Perl bindings,
so you can actually make CUPS calls,

00:22:59.810 --> 00:23:02.950
create printers,
and print directly without going through

00:23:03.040 --> 00:23:04.210
the print system from those languages.

00:23:04.220 --> 00:23:06.800
There's fax support,
which is important if you saw the

00:23:06.800 --> 00:23:08.980
keynote last night or yesterday morning.

00:23:08.980 --> 00:23:11.090
IPP collections,
which allows us to do some

00:23:11.090 --> 00:23:13.780
better error handling,
and improved PPD support.

00:23:13.780 --> 00:23:18.910
The PPD parser in 1.1.19 is much
tighter than it was in earlier versions.

00:23:18.920 --> 00:23:23.580
It'll flag PPDs that are bad much
more easily or much more clearly.

00:23:23.580 --> 00:23:26.690
And it also allows access
to most of the PPD keywords,

00:23:26.820 --> 00:23:29.410
whereas the earlier
PPD libraries did not.

00:23:31.860 --> 00:23:36.730
GIMP Print has been out there,
has been used by a lot of our users,

00:23:36.860 --> 00:23:37.920
as has HPI.js.

00:23:37.920 --> 00:23:40.780
This is actually one of the most
exciting things about using CUPS,

00:23:40.780 --> 00:23:44.090
is that the world of open source
printer drivers is available to

00:23:44.130 --> 00:23:46.020
our users and to our developers.

00:23:46.020 --> 00:23:47.480
And this has really been
great over the years,

00:23:47.480 --> 00:23:49.490
supporting some older printers
that maybe the vendors haven't

00:23:49.500 --> 00:23:50.760
gotten around to supporting.

00:23:51.220 --> 00:23:53.710
As you can see,
GIMP Print supports over 500 printers

00:23:53.710 --> 00:23:55.490
from most of the major printer vendors.

00:23:55.520 --> 00:23:58.520
HPI.js supports a couple
hundred HP printer models.

00:23:58.520 --> 00:24:01.470
That's a lot of legacy printer support,
and it's been great for us.

00:24:01.500 --> 00:24:04.640
There's also been some important
support from some of our Linux cousins.

00:24:04.650 --> 00:24:07.630
If you go to linuxprinting.org,
you'll see some great Mac OS X printing

00:24:07.740 --> 00:24:09.540
pages supporting these two packages.

00:24:09.540 --> 00:24:11.490
So I encourage you to go look at those.

00:24:11.490 --> 00:24:14.540
This wasn't stolen for the keynote,
and I'm very happy.

00:24:14.540 --> 00:24:17.010
I get to announce today that
GIMP Print's actually going to

00:24:17.010 --> 00:24:18.480
be part of Darwin and Panther.

00:24:18.480 --> 00:24:20.960
So we'll have those drivers
in there by default.

00:24:20.960 --> 00:24:21.200
Ready?

00:24:21.220 --> 00:24:22.800
There you go.

00:24:27.020 --> 00:24:27.550
But there's more.

00:24:27.580 --> 00:24:30.160
As you saw the keynote,
there's also Fax in Panther.

00:24:30.160 --> 00:24:32.660
And following our printing tradition,
what we wanted to do is

00:24:32.660 --> 00:24:34.910
take an open source core,
put that into Darwin,

00:24:34.910 --> 00:24:37.010
and then build on top of
it in our commercial OS.

00:24:37.040 --> 00:24:37.810
So we used eFax.

00:24:37.810 --> 00:24:39.880
If anybody knows the
Fax landscape out there,

00:24:39.880 --> 00:24:42.470
there's really two different
open source projects.

00:24:42.480 --> 00:24:44.640
There's eFax, which is very small.

00:24:44.640 --> 00:24:47.080
It's not an incredibly active project.

00:24:47.080 --> 00:24:48.820
And there's HiLiFax,
which will do everything

00:24:48.820 --> 00:24:50.820
you'd ever want in faxing,
and it's a lot larger.

00:24:50.820 --> 00:24:53.030
We actually went with a smaller project.

00:24:53.030 --> 00:24:55.230
It seemed to fit our goals more cleanly.

00:24:55.740 --> 00:24:56.680
So we've got eFax.

00:24:56.740 --> 00:24:59.880
It's in the Darwin repository right now,
and it'll be in Panther,

00:24:59.880 --> 00:25:01.180
and it's available for you.

00:25:04.590 --> 00:25:10.890
I'll be talking Thursday, much longer,
about printing in Mac OS X Panther,

00:25:10.940 --> 00:25:14.630
but also going over some of
these Darwin printing projects.

00:25:14.680 --> 00:25:16.420
So again,
the most important message I have

00:25:16.430 --> 00:25:18.650
for you today is we have three
projects now that are tied to

00:25:19.030 --> 00:25:20.260
printing that are all in Darwin.

00:25:20.260 --> 00:25:22.340
We have CUPS, the print server.

00:25:22.340 --> 00:25:24.310
We have GIMP Print,
a set of printer drivers.

00:25:24.320 --> 00:25:25.960
And we have eFax for our fax port.

00:25:25.960 --> 00:25:27.680
All three of those projects
are live every day.

00:25:27.680 --> 00:25:30.210
I encourage you to,
if you're interested in any of those,

00:25:30.210 --> 00:25:31.670
track our changes every day.

00:25:32.100 --> 00:25:32.660
Send us mail.

00:25:32.660 --> 00:25:34.360
Let us know, hey, this change was wrong.

00:25:34.360 --> 00:25:37.040
Hey, we should pick up this other change
that was coming from another project.

00:25:37.040 --> 00:25:40.210
We do this so we can be incredibly
transparent to you so you know what

00:25:40.210 --> 00:25:43.160
we're doing for our OSes before
we have to release the GM version.

00:25:43.160 --> 00:25:45.740
So anything you do to help
us would be much appreciated.

