00:25:58.830 --> 00:26:02.620
So XFree86 has a fairly long
history on Mac OS X comparatively,

00:26:02.620 --> 00:26:05.030
at least as far as this
operating system goes.

00:26:05.040 --> 00:26:11.860
The initial Darwin support was in
the late 2000 with XFree86 4.0.2.

00:26:11.860 --> 00:26:16.220
In this release,
you had to shut down core graphics.

00:26:16.280 --> 00:26:19.620
XFree86 would talk through the
IOCAD directly to the hardware.

00:26:19.620 --> 00:26:22.570
Then in subsequent releases,
we added the ability to

00:26:22.570 --> 00:26:25.840
run in parallel with Aqua,
where you could have two separate virtual

00:26:25.840 --> 00:26:27.480
screens and switch back and forth.

00:26:28.420 --> 00:26:31.300
And then we added a
rootless mode in early 2002,

00:26:31.300 --> 00:26:37.320
and that's culminated in the 4.3 release,
which gives us faster 2D and

00:26:37.320 --> 00:26:39.760
hardware-accelerated OpenGL.

00:26:39.760 --> 00:26:41.740
Now, of course,
the thing that's missing from here,

00:26:41.740 --> 00:26:46.750
or is yet to come,
is the 1.0 release of Apple's X11.app,

00:26:46.820 --> 00:26:49.080
which is a very exciting
thing in this area.

00:26:49.080 --> 00:26:55.070
And as most of you probably know,
that's based on the XFree86 code base.

00:26:55.160 --> 00:26:59.640
At least their current beta is based
on XFree86 4.0 and Apple's X11.app.

00:26:59.640 --> 00:27:02.960
So, what are we planning to
do in the XFree86 project?

00:27:02.980 --> 00:27:05.060
Of course,
the most important thing for us

00:27:05.110 --> 00:27:10.860
is to get the lot of good changes
that Apple's made in releasing X11

00:27:11.120 --> 00:27:13.930
merged into the XFree86 code base.

00:27:13.940 --> 00:27:21.220
There's a win-win situation if we can
get Apple's X11.app and the XFree86 open

00:27:21.220 --> 00:27:24.420
source release tightly synchronized.

00:27:24.420 --> 00:27:26.490
And we're working hard on that.

00:27:26.540 --> 00:27:30.360
And what really makes that
possible is this XPlugin API,

00:27:30.360 --> 00:27:36.610
which allows open source developers to
really write high-performance X servers.

00:27:36.640 --> 00:27:41.300
The problem we had sort of at the
end of the 4.3 development is that

00:27:41.300 --> 00:27:44.440
essentially what we're trying to do is
we're trying to write an XWindow server

00:27:44.440 --> 00:27:47.840
on top of another Windows server,
which is Core Graphics.

00:27:47.840 --> 00:27:53.380
And there weren't existing public
APIs in Mac OS X that allowed us

00:27:53.380 --> 00:27:56.370
low enough level access to get
the performance we really needed.

00:27:57.580 --> 00:28:02.860
So, in discussions with Apple,
what really emerged was that

00:28:02.980 --> 00:28:05.410
actually Core Graphics has
all the capability we need,

00:28:05.480 --> 00:28:12.610
but that there aren't -- the APIs we
needed aren't private APIs that are

00:28:12.620 --> 00:28:15.900
hidden and not exposed and therefore
not suitable for open source code.

00:28:15.900 --> 00:28:19.980
So, what XPlugin is,
is it's a library that is

00:28:20.010 --> 00:28:26.290
exactly what you need to write an
X server on Mac OS X and no more.

00:28:26.300 --> 00:28:27.300
So, it's fairly easy for us to write an
X server on Mac OS X and no more.

00:28:27.300 --> 00:28:29.900
So, it's fairly easy for Apple to
maintain as they go forward.

00:28:29.940 --> 00:28:32.940
And it also allows open source
developers sort of a green

00:28:32.940 --> 00:28:37.540
light to go ahead and write very
high-performance X servers on Mac OS X.

00:28:37.540 --> 00:28:45.220
And this is really the big news as
far as my part of the talk is that --

00:28:45.400 --> 00:28:48.450
Apple's X11 we would think of as
the first implementation of an

00:28:48.520 --> 00:28:50.400
X server using this X plugin API.

00:28:50.400 --> 00:28:52.170
And actually, if you check it out,
you can check out their

00:28:52.170 --> 00:28:52.980
beta 3 source code.

00:28:52.980 --> 00:28:56.020
You'll see it's XFree86 with
acceleration features added in,

00:28:56.020 --> 00:28:59.520
and they're just using OpenGeo,
Core Graphics, and this X plugin API.

00:29:00.540 --> 00:29:04.340
So we'd also,
in addition to making things go faster,

00:29:04.340 --> 00:29:06.280
we'd also like to make them better.

00:29:06.280 --> 00:29:11.390
So we're working on adding multiple
visuals of various classes and depths.

00:29:11.390 --> 00:29:15.860
The common problem here is that you
want to display an 8-bit pseudocolor

00:29:15.860 --> 00:29:18.640
visual and a 24-bit true color display.

00:29:18.640 --> 00:29:21.110
