00:39:36.530 --> 00:39:39.790
It's a cross-platform project.

00:39:39.790 --> 00:39:41.450
It's standards-based.

00:39:41.450 --> 00:39:45.340
It currently is running on Mac OS X.

00:39:45.340 --> 00:39:48.160
It has a classic build as well.

00:39:48.160 --> 00:39:51.860
It runs under Windows and Linux.

00:39:51.860 --> 00:39:58.690
And the Mac OS X build has both a
CFM-based and a Mac OS-based build.

00:39:58.690 --> 00:40:05.740
It's a modular build,
meaning that the underlying protocols,

00:40:05.740 --> 00:40:10.330
like TCP and Apple Talk,
are plug-in modules.

00:40:10.340 --> 00:40:16.170
There's the flexibility to add
new protocols via that modularity.

00:40:16.170 --> 00:40:20.430
And in fact, this year,
that flexibility has been used.

00:40:21.500 --> 00:40:27.080
And the use has been to
add Rendezvous support.

00:40:27.410 --> 00:40:31.270
It's got a large adoption.

00:40:31.270 --> 00:40:35.070
A lot of titles are using it,
a lot more titles coming out.

00:40:35.230 --> 00:40:39.100
Most of these titles happen to be
games because of the NetSprocket API,

00:40:39.100 --> 00:40:40.260
and that's what people know.

00:40:40.260 --> 00:40:43.940
But there's no reason that
it is a games-only API.

00:40:44.190 --> 00:40:48.730
You can use it for any kind of
quick networking that you'd like.

00:40:51.020 --> 00:40:53.520
It has a few simple layers.

00:40:53.520 --> 00:40:56.340
Your application can talk to
any of the layers directly.

00:40:56.340 --> 00:41:01.020
There's the game interface,
which is the NetSprocket API.

00:41:01.020 --> 00:41:02.750
It's very easy to use.

00:41:02.750 --> 00:41:04.620
It handles multiple users.

00:41:04.620 --> 00:41:06.240
You can group users.

00:41:06.240 --> 00:41:11.160
All that high level stuff is very
easy to do via that protocol.

00:41:12.060 --> 00:41:16.490
There's the protocol module,
which is the former OpenPlay,

00:41:16.490 --> 00:41:20.300
and it deals directly with
the abstraction of the

00:41:20.310 --> 00:41:25.580
modules that you deal with,
TCP, AppleTalk, and you can talk to those

00:41:25.890 --> 00:41:30.490
modules directly as well,
whichever you would like.

00:41:32.410 --> 00:41:36.290
The game interface, like I said,
provides the easiest way

00:41:36.290 --> 00:41:39.180
to add networking to your
game or other application.

00:41:39.180 --> 00:41:44.480
It has player management,
game management, packet management,

00:41:44.480 --> 00:41:52.070
and again,
it runs on all the different platforms.

00:41:52.420 --> 00:41:54.940
The protocol interface
is fairly low level.

00:41:54.940 --> 00:42:01.300
It's much closer to like
a sockets based protocol.

00:42:01.300 --> 00:42:06.930
It has the protocol agnostic design
so that you can use one API and

00:42:06.930 --> 00:42:10.860
you can talk over Apple Talk,
TCP IP, or Rendezvous.

00:42:12.520 --> 00:42:17.010
It has the IP module for all platforms.

00:42:17.160 --> 00:42:22.230
It has Apple Talk for
Mac OS and Mac OS X.

00:42:22.230 --> 00:42:26.920
And it has Rendezvous for Mac OS X.

00:42:29.140 --> 00:42:35.480
The next step, of course,
is the newest plug-in module

00:42:35.480 --> 00:42:43.100
that was developed by Freeverse
Software and committed back to the

00:42:43.100 --> 00:42:47.050
community for everybody to use.

00:42:47.050 --> 00:42:51.110
So that should give you an idea of
how easy it is to add a new networking

00:42:51.110 --> 00:42:51.110
API if you happen to have the need.

00:42:55.750 --> 00:43:00.120
If you want to know more
about OpenPlay and everything

00:43:00.580 --> 00:43:06.870
that's going on with that,
there's not an OpenPlay specific

00:43:06.870 --> 00:43:10.540
session this year,
